First bird of the year: juvenile white ibis. 

One is never completely alone on a hike and today’s was no exception. IYKYK. I like to think that these are sisters coming to say hello in the ethereal mist. 

The ibis symbolizes great wisdom and the ability to work magic. They were symbols of good luck and to wear an ibis feather would bring good fortune. 

This and that bowl of b.e.ps hopefully makes me doubly blessed. And I’m passing on all these New Years blessings to my oldest and dearest (IYKYK).

Where Copper is King: In the ancient village of Lahij on the southern slopes of the Greater Caucasus in Azerbaijan we met Reza a sixth-generation coppersmith working in the 300-year-old studio that his fore-bearers opened in 1725. Lahij is one of the most ancient human settlements in Azerbaijan and has been an important center of craftsmanship since the Medieval period. UNESCO named the copper work from Lahij to the list of Intangible Cultural Heritage and magnificent works of copper from this village can be found in some of the most notable museums of the world. Also pictured is Reza’s nephew, marking the seventh-generation of Reza’s family to keep the art of copper craftsmanship in the family. Last but not least - Reza’s wife Noor made us a delicious Azeri lunch. @natgeoexpeditions

The Weekly Florida

Here are my Top 10 books for 2023. Having read a record (for me) of 44 books this year - I thought it worthy of passing on my 10 favorites (with the disclaimer that there are many reader’s 2023 release favorites still in my TBR stack). 

Among the 10 I’d like to call out three specifically: 

The Comfort of Crows - @margaret.renkl 

The incredibly wise Margaret Renkl, in her third book, fully inherits the baton of contemplative nature writing from Annie Dillard and Mary Oliver but with her own amazing fresh voice. Her stunningly beautiful prose is anchored in family, experience, science and truth. Her seemingly ordinary walks around her 1/2 acre backyard or through a nearby city park contain as much wonder and adventure as any of the greatest travel tomes. Margaret Renkl is a treasure and a modern-day St. Francis bearing messages of hope, beauty and urgency to care for the ever-shrinking sacred spaces of nature. Bonus! The book is exquisitely illustrated by the incredibly talented @billyrenkl 

How to Say Babylon - @safiyasinclair 

 If for no other reason- read this for the absolutely phenomenal writing. This book had some of the most breathtaking, lyrical writing I’ve come across in many years. I read and reread and reread again words, sentences, whole paragraphs, just to savor again and again; and always in abject wonder of their precision and beauty. Add to this the story of Sinclair’s journey to break free of her strict Rastafarian upbringing, and you have an extremely compelling and fascinating memoir - I could not put it down! 

Calling for a Blanket Dance - @oscarhokeah 

Calling for a Blanket Dance is a masterpiece in multicultural storytelling and Hokeah’s prose is subtle, raw, and searingly beautiful. The book “stitches a generational quilt of rich themes: giftgiving, second, chances, reclaiming cultures, family, loyalty, and the incredible search for home.” I rank the stories that Hokeah weaves throughout the book as powerful and as important as Harjo/Waititi’s “Reservation Dogs”. This is exquisite literary fiction and Hokeah is a fresh and important voice within the emerging renaissance of indigenous literature.

Happy New Year and Happy Reading!
